  On autoresearch

  I fetched the actual repo. A few things Gemini/Cursor didn't mention:

  It requires a single NVIDIA GPU. Karpathy is explicit — MPS/Apple Silicon is not supported in the main repo. Your M1 can't run it natively. Your GCP Spot
  VM could, but only if it's provisioned with an NVIDIA GPU (H100 in the README). If your Spot VM is CPU-only or uses a different accelerator, this won't
  work as-is.

  It's not a general software-engineering loop. autoresearch modifies exactly one file (train.py) which is a GPT training script. It optimizes neural network
   architecture and hyperparameters by running 5-minute training runs and measuring val_bpb (validation bits per byte). It has nothing to do with patching
  api.py, orchestrator.py, or any JARVIS infrastructure code. That's Ouroboros' domain.

  The "two hemispheres" framing is architecturally correct and worth keeping. Gemini nailed this:
  - Ouroboros = autonomous software engineer — patches code, runs tests, commits
  - autoresearch = autonomous ML researcher — iterates on model training, improves weights

  They operate on different timescales (seconds vs. hours), different failure modes (a bad patch vs. a diverging training run), and different assets (Python
  code vs. PyTorch checkpoints). Mixing them would be a mistake.

  However, it's premature. Right now J-Prime is a served inference endpoint from your golden image, not a model you're actively training weights for.
  autoresearch would only matter if/when you're doing LoRA fine-tuning or full pre-training on your own data — which is a later-stage concern. The analogy
  would be building the research lab before the factory is operational.

